    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "act": "COLD OPEN",
      "t_start": 0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "A metal, a semiconductor, and an insulator. They differ in one thing: a forbidden band of energies between the filled states and the empty ones. Where does that gap come from?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.23,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-band-gap/clips/B01.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "act": "COLD OPEN",
      "t_start": 9,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "It opens because at one special wavelength, the lattice forces an electron to stand still \u2014 and it can do that two different ways. One way sits lower in energy. The gap is the distance between them.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.15,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-band-gap/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "act": "THE QUESTION",
      "t_start": 18,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "What wavelength is special \u2014 and why does standing still come in two flavors with a forbidden zone between them?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "card",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "headline": "What wavelength is special \u2014 and why does standing still come\u2026",
            "eyebrow": "THE QUESTION",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B03.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "headline": "Two standing waves, same kinetic energy.\nDifferent positions \u2192 different potential energy \u2192 gap.",
        "dek": "The band gap: why a periodic lattice splits electron energies"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 6.27,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-band-gap/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "t_start": 27,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Free electrons move as plane waves. Their energy climbs as a parabola: E equals h-bar-squared k-squared over 2m. No forbidden zones \u2014 every energy is allowed.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.47,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-band-gap/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "t_start": 38,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Now add a crystal. The lattice repeats every a. Bragg reflection couples waves at k equals pi over a to the wave at minus pi over a \u2014 they share the same wavelength, 2a.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.07,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-band-gap/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 49,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "At the zone boundary, the forward and backward waves are equal. They mix into two standing waves. The plus combination peaks on the ion sites. The minus combination peaks between them.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.95,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-band-gap/clips/B06.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 61,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Both standing waves have the same kinetic energy. But the plus wave sits on the attractive ion cores \u2014 it sees lower potential energy. The minus wave avoids the cores \u2014 it sees higher potential energy. That difference is the gap.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.58,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-band-gap/clips/B07.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "act": "THE IMPLICATION",
      "t_start": 72,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The gap size equals twice the Fourier component of the lattice potential at the reciprocal lattice vector. Stronger ions mean a wider gap. The gap is the lattice writing itself into the electron spectrum.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.54,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-band-gap/clips/B08.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B08.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "act": "THE IMPLICATION",
      "t_start": 82,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Fill electrons up to the gap and you get an insulator. Fill halfway and the Fermi level cuts through a band \u2014 a metal. A small gap of 1 electron-volt makes a semiconductor.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.16,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-band-gap/clips/B09.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B09.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "act": "THE EXAMPLE",
      "t_start": 92,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Illustrative: silicon lattice constant 5.4 angstroms, band gap 1.1 eV. The Fourier component at the zone boundary is about 0.55 eV \u2014 half the gap, as the theory predicts.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.74,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-band-gap/clips/B10.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B10.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "act": "RECAP",
      "t_start": 104,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "At the Bragg wavelength the electron must stand still \u2014 two ways. One sits on the ions. One avoids them. Their energy difference is the forbidden gap. That is where band gaps come from.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "card",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "headline": "At the Bragg wavelength the electron must stand still \u2014 two\u2026",
            "eyebrow": "RECAP",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B11.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "headline": "Gap = 2|V_G|.\n\u03c8\u208a on ions (low E), \u03c8\u208b between ions (high E).",
        "dek": "Bragg reflection at k = \u03c0/a forces two standing waves. Their potential energy difference is the band gap."
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-band-gap/mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
